  "prompt": "Why do people avoid south facing homes?",
  "response": "People may avoid south-facing homes for several reasons, though perceptions can vary by culture and region:\n\n1. Climate considerations:\n- In hot climates, south-facing homes can receive excessive direct sunlight, leading to higher cooling costs\n- Increased heat absorption can make interiors uncomfortably warm\n- Higher energy expenses for air conditioning\n\n2. Feng Shui beliefs:\n- Some cultures consider south-facing homes less auspicious\n- Potential negative energy flow according to traditional principles\n\n3. Gardening challenges:\n- Direct southern exposure might cause plants to dry out quickly\n- Potential sun damage to landscaping and gardens\n\n4. Potential glare issues:\n- Excessive sunlight can create glare on windows and screens\n- Potential discomfort for residents\n\n5. Personal comfort preferences:\n- Some people find constant direct sunlight overwhelming\n- Preference for more moderate light exposure\n\nHowever, south-facing homes can also have advantages:\n- Better natural light\n- Potential solar heating benefits in colder climates\n- More consistent daylight\n\nThe perception of south-facing homes varies greatly depending on local climate, personal preferences, and cultural beliefs. What might be considered a disadvantage in one region could be an advantage in another.",
